        <h1><i class="fas fa-cloud-moon"></i> Dark Matter and Temporal Horizon</h1>
        <p>
            In the Unified Universe Theory, dark matter might be understood as matter so dense that it crosses the temporal horizon. The temporal horizon is the boundary beyond which matter or energy is no longer in the present moment of our observable universe.
        </p>
        <p>
            When the pushback force exceeds the temporal expansion force, the matter effectively moves out of our observable timeline, making it invisible to us in the usual sense. However, the gravitational effects of this matter are still felt in our universe, which is why we can observe the effects of dark matter without being able to see it directly.
        </p>

        <h2><i class="fas fa-calculator"></i> Mathematical Prediction</h2>
        <p>
            The point at which matter crosses the temporal horizon can be predicted by the following equation:
        </p>
        <div class="math-equation">
            <span>F<sub>p</sub> = F<sub>t</sub> - G * (M * ρ / r²)</span>
        </div>
        <p>
            In this equation:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>F<sub>p</sub></strong> represents the pushback force exerted by the mass of the object.</li>
            <li><strong>F<sub>t</sub></strong> is the temporal expansion force.</li>
            <li><strong>G</strong> is the gravitational constant.</li>
            <li><strong>M</strong> is the mass of the object.</li>
            <li><strong>ρ</strong> is the density of the object.</li>
            <li><strong>r</strong> is the distance from the object to the observer.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            When <strong>F<sub>p</sub></strong> exceeds <strong>F<sub>t</sub></strong>, the matter crosses the temporal horizon and dips out of our observable universe. This threshold marks the point at which the matter is no longer in our current temporal frame, becoming "dark" to us while still exerting gravitational effects.
        </p>

        <!-- Simplified Explanation -->
        <h2><i class="fas fa-lightbulb"></i> Simplified Explanation</h2>
        <p>
            Imagine you're looking at a pond with a floating object on the surface. If the object gets too heavy, it sinks below the surface and you can't see it anymore. But you can still see the ripples it makes on the surface. Dark matter is like that heavy object—it's so dense that it sinks out of our view (the present time), but we can still see the "ripples" it causes, like gravity affecting galaxies.
        </p>

